all+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%289%2F1%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_sour=
ce=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a )

The Data Costs

Artnet has always reported very high annual costs for software development =
relative to the improvement of its database. Some speculate those high cost=
s are related to software debt. After all, the database was built in the 19=
90s, long before the very significant advances in the industry. Artnet vehe=
mently objects to any suggestion their technology is lagging. (Users can be=
 their own judge.) But the company=E2=80=99s income statement suggests that=
 it shells out more than $2.5 million per year for product development.

I won=E2=80=99t go into the complexities of the accounting statements, but =
it does strike me as possible that the auditors required Artnet to take a w=
rite-down on some expenses, including maintenance costs, that were previous=
ly treated as capital investments. (You can look for yourself here ( https:=
//www.artnet.com/investor-relations/annual-reports/240831_artnet_AnnualRepo=
rt_EN.pdf?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%289%2F17%2F24%29&utm_con=
tent=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%289%2F1%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&=
utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c60617da42abd12a ).) What also stands=
 out in the annual report=E2=80=94besides the growing losses on what appear=
s to be a stable business=E2=80=94is the fact that beyond Hans Neuendorf=E2=
=80=99s consulting arrangement with Artnet, there are other related-party a=
rrangements, such as a =E2=82=AC66,000 payment to a member of the managemen=
t board for design work, and a =E2=82=AC118,000 consultation payment to ano=
ther member of the board. There are also loans in the amounts
of =E2=82=AC492,000 from an Artnet executive and =E2=82=AC511,000 from Gale=
rie Neuendorf, as well as that additional $1 million loan from a private pa=
rty in New York.

If you were a shareholder in Artnet, you might be wondering why a
moderately healthy company, which admittedly has some low-margin businesses=
, keeps falling behind. That=E2=80=99s the background to the upcoming annua=
l general meeting. If and when it gets scheduled, I=E2=80=99ll be curious t=
o learn more=E2=80=94as I=E2=80=99m sure you will be, as well.

Endnotes=E2=80=A6

I don=E2=80=99t want to leave you with dry financial talk. So let=E2=80=99s=
 turn to a little poetic discourse. New Yorker critic Jackson Arn has an af=
fecting review ( https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2024/09/23/monet-the-re=
stless-vision-jackie-wullschlager-book-review?utm_campaign=3DWall+Power+-+S=
UBSCRIBERS+%289%2F17%2F24%29&utm_content=3DWall+Power+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%289%2F=
1%2F24%29&utm_medium=3Demail_action&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io&utm_term=3Df6c=
60617da42abd12a ) of Jackie Wullschl=C3=A4ger=E2=80=99s new biography of Cl=
aude Monet=E2=80=94stunningly, the first-ever English-language work on the =
artist=E2=80=99s life.

It=E2=80=99s a fascinating essay=E2=80=94especially given the 150th anniver=
sary of the birth of impressionism, in April, and the debut of an important=
 exhibition on the theme at
the National Gallery in Washington, D.C. It=E2=80=99s also an important rem=
inder, as Arn writes, that the future success of the impressionist movement=
 was hardly obvious to the artists who toiled over these now historic works=
:

* [Wullschl=C3=A4ger] quotes from a letter in which Monet, having received =
twenty-five hundred francs for a =E2=80=9CHaystack,=E2=80=9D begs the buyer=
 to tell everybody that the figure was five thousand, and right there, as t=
hough accompanied by violin plucks, is our guy=E2=80=94mischievous, cocky, =
positively gleeful about the fine art of selling fine art. She is equally s=
harp on her hero=E2=80=99s day-to-day: at Giverny, where he spent decades, =
he would rise at dawn, paint for hours, eat like a starved animal, get back=
 to work, and keep at it until dinner at seven. Sleeping, eating, painting,=
 haggling, and selling, all stages of
one vigorous process.

I=E2=80=99m looking forward to reading Wullschl=C3=A4ger=E2=80=99s book.

That=E2=80=99s it for me today. I=E2=80=99ll be back on Sunday with a look =
at the mid-season sales.

Speak to you then,
M

