205d65fb06221e9c80c7fd36" style=3D"color:#d40000;text-decoration:none;font-=
weight:bold" class=3D"sdf">explain</a></u> earlier this year, has attracted=
 <b>R=C3=BCdiger Weng</b>, who is looking to oust Pabst=E2=80=99s father, <=
b>Hans Neuendorf</b>, the company=E2=80=99s founder and former C.E.O., and =
the rest of the Neuendorf family from control. Per the report, at the end o=
f last year, Weng owned 28.83 percent of Artnet=E2=80=99s stock through his=
 firm, Weng Fine Art, which eclipsed the
26.65 percent position held by Galerie Neuendorf, the Berlin-based entity c=
ontrolled by Hans. The two sides are competing for the votes of a handful o=
f other large investors, with the issue expected to come to a head at the a=
nnual general meeting, a shareholder gathering originally slated for August=
 but that remains unscheduled.<br/><br/>The last time I wrote about Artnet,=
 the company was unhappy with my piece. One of Artnet=E2=80=99s complaints =
was that I had misstated Neuendorf=E2=80=99s compensation. I had written th=
at Neuendorf=E2=80=99s consultancy agreement with Artnet included a fee of =
$325,000. (The correct number, revealed in the annual report, is =E2=82=AC3=
36,000 for 2022. That fee was reduced to =E2=82=AC161,000 in 2023.) For thi=
s article, I sent emails to Pabst and his brother, <b>Albert Neuendorf</b>,=
 Artnet=E2=80=99s chief strategy officer, asking to discuss the company=E2=
=80=99s financial statements. I received no reply. I wrote to them again th=
is morning, and included their sister<b> Sophie
Neuendorf</b> as well. They did not respond to my requests for comment. <br=
/></td>
